#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:3
msgid "NumPy 1.15.0 Release Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:5
msgid ""
"NumPy 1.15.0 is a release with an unusual number of cleanups, many "
"deprecations of old functions, and improvements to many existing functions. "
"Please read the detailed descriptions below to see if you are affected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:9
msgid ""
"For testing, we have switched to pytest as a replacement for the no longer "
"maintained nose framework. The old nose based interface remains for "
"downstream projects who may still be using it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:13
msgid ""
"The Python versions supported by this release are 2.7, 3.4-3.7. The wheels "
"are linked with OpenBLAS v0.3.0, which should fix some of the linalg "
"problems reported for NumPy 1.14."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:19
msgid "Highlights"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:21
msgid "NumPy has switched to pytest for testing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:22
msgid "A new  `numpy.printoptions` context manager."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:23
msgid "Many improvements to the histogram functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:24
msgid "Support for unicode field names in python 2.7."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:25
msgid "Improved support for PyPy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:26
msgid "Fixes and improvements to `numpy.einsum`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:30
msgid "New functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:32
msgid ""
"`numpy.gcd` and `numpy.lcm`, to compute the greatest common divisor and "
"least common multiple."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:35
msgid ""
"`numpy.ma.stack`, the `numpy.stack` array-joining function generalized to "
"masked arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:38
msgid ""
"`numpy.quantile` function, an interface to ``percentile`` without factors of "
"100"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:41
msgid ""
"`numpy.nanquantile` function, an interface to ``nanpercentile`` without "
"factors of 100"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:44
msgid ""
"`numpy.printoptions`, a context manager that sets print options temporarily "
"for the scope of the ``with`` block::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:47
msgid ""
">>> with np.printoptions(precision=2):\n"
"...     print(np.array([2.0]) / 3)\n"
"[0.67]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:51
msgid ""
"`numpy.histogram_bin_edges`, a function to get the edges of the bins used by "
"a histogram without needing to calculate the histogram."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:54
msgid ""
"C functions `npy_get_floatstatus_barrier` and "
"`npy_clear_floatstatus_barrier` have been added to deal with compiler "
"optimization changing the order of operations.  See below for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:60
msgid "Deprecations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:62
msgid ""
"Aliases of builtin `pickle` functions are deprecated, in favor of their "
"unaliased ``pickle.<func>`` names:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:65
msgid "`numpy.loads`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:66
msgid "`numpy.core.numeric.load`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:67
msgid "`numpy.core.numeric.loads`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:68
msgid "`numpy.ma.loads`, `numpy.ma.dumps`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:69
msgid ""
"`numpy.ma.load`, `numpy.ma.dump` - these functions already failed on python "
"3 when called with a string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:72
msgid ""
"Multidimensional indexing with anything but a tuple is deprecated. This "
"means that the index list in ``ind = [slice(None), 0]; arr[ind]`` should be "
"changed to a tuple, e.g., ``ind = [slice(None), 0]; arr[tuple(ind)]`` or "
"``arr[(slice(None), 0)]``. That change is necessary to avoid ambiguity in "
"expressions such as ``arr[[[0, 1], [0, 1]]]``, currently interpreted as "
"``arr[array([0, 1]), array([0, 1])]``, that will be interpreted as "
"``arr[array([[0, 1], [0, 1]])]`` in the future."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:80
msgid ""
"Imports from the following sub-modules are deprecated, they will be removed "
"at some future date."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:83
msgid "`numpy.testing.utils`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:84
msgid "`numpy.testing.decorators`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:85
msgid "`numpy.testing.nosetester`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:86
msgid "`numpy.testing.noseclasses`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:87
msgid "`numpy.core.umath_tests`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:89
msgid ""
"Giving a generator to `numpy.sum` is now deprecated. This was undocumented "
"behavior, but worked. Previously, it would calculate the sum of the "
"generator expression.  In the future, it might return a different result. "
"Use ``np.sum(np.from_iter(generator))`` or the built-in Python ``sum`` "
"instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:94
msgid ""
"Users of the C-API should call ``PyArrayResolveWriteBackIfCopy`` or "
"``PyArray_DiscardWritebackIfCopy`` on any array with the ``WRITEBACKIFCOPY`` "
"flag set, before deallocating the array. A deprecation warning will be "
"emitted if those calls are not used when needed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:99
msgid ""
"Users of ``nditer`` should use the nditer object as a context manager "
"anytime one of the iterator operands is writeable, so that numpy can manage "
"writeback semantics, or should call ``it.close()``. A `RuntimeWarning` may "
"be emitted otherwise in these cases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:104
msgid ""
"The ``normed`` argument of ``np.histogram``, deprecated long ago in 1.6.0, "
"now emits a ``DeprecationWarning``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:109
msgid "Future Changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:111
msgid "NumPy 1.16 will drop support for Python 3.4."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:112
msgid "NumPy 1.17 will drop support for Python 2.7."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:116
msgid "Compatibility notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:119
msgid "Compiled testing modules renamed and made private"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:120
msgid "The following compiled modules have been renamed and made private:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:122
msgid "``umath_tests`` -> ``_umath_tests``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:123
msgid "``test_rational`` -> ``_rational_tests``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:124
msgid "``multiarray_tests`` -> ``_multiarray_tests``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:125
msgid "``struct_ufunc_test`` -> ``_struct_ufunc_tests``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:126
msgid "``operand_flag_tests`` -> ``_operand_flag_tests``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:128
msgid ""
"The ``umath_tests`` module is still available for backwards compatibility, "
"but will be removed in the future."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:132
msgid ""
"The ``NpzFile`` returned by ``np.savez`` is now a ``collections.abc.Mapping``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:133
msgid ""
"This means it behaves like a readonly dictionary, and has a new ``."
"values()`` method and ``len()`` implementation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:136
msgid ""
"For python 3, this means that ``.iteritems()``, ``.iterkeys()`` have been "
"deprecated, and ``.keys()`` and ``.items()`` now return views and not lists. "
"This is consistent with how the builtin ``dict`` type changed between python "
"2 and python 3."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:142
msgid "Under certain conditions, ``nditer`` must be used in a context manager"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:143
msgid ""
"When using an `numpy.nditer` with the ``\"writeonly\"`` or ``\"readwrite\"`` "
"flags, there are some circumstances where nditer doesn't actually give you a "
"view of the writable array. Instead, it gives you a copy, and if you make "
"changes to the copy, nditer later writes those changes back into your actual "
"array. Currently, this writeback occurs when the array objects are garbage "
"collected, which makes this API error-prone on CPython and entirely broken "
"on PyPy. Therefore, ``nditer`` should now be used as a context manager "
"whenever it is used with writeable arrays, e.g., ``with np.nditer(...) as "
"it: ...``. You may also explicitly call ``it.close()`` for cases where a "
"context manager is unusable, for instance in generator expressions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:155
msgid "Numpy has switched to using pytest instead of nose for testing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:156
msgid ""
"The last nose release was 1.3.7 in June, 2015, and development of that tool "
"has ended, consequently NumPy has now switched to using pytest. The old "
"decorators and nose tools that were previously used by some downstream "
"projects remain available, but will not be maintained. The standard testing "
"utilities, ``assert_almost_equal`` and such, are not be affected by this "
"change except for the nose specific functions ``import_nose`` and "
"``raises``. Those functions are not used in numpy, but are kept for "
"downstream compatibility."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:165
msgid "Numpy no longer monkey-patches ``ctypes`` with ``__array_interface__``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:166
msgid ""
"Previously numpy added ``__array_interface__`` attributes to all the integer "
"types from ``ctypes``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:170
msgid ""
"``np.ma.notmasked_contiguous`` and ``np.ma.flatnotmasked_contiguous`` always "
"return lists"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:171
msgid ""
"This is the documented behavior, but previously the result could be any of "
"slice, None, or list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:174
msgid ""
"All downstream users seem to check for the ``None`` result from "
"``flatnotmasked_contiguous`` and replace it with ``[]``.  Those callers will "
"continue to work as before."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:179
msgid ""
"``np.squeeze`` restores old behavior of objects that cannot handle an "
"``axis`` argument"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:180
msgid ""
"Prior to version ``1.7.0``, `numpy.squeeze` did not have an ``axis`` "
"argument and all empty axes were removed by default. The incorporation of an "
"``axis`` argument made it possible to selectively squeeze single or multiple "
"empty axes, but the old API expectation was not respected because axes could "
"still be selectively removed (silent success) from an object expecting all "
"empty axes to be removed. That silent, selective removal of empty axes for "
"objects expecting the old behavior has been fixed and the old behavior "
"restored."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:189
msgid "unstructured void array's ``.item`` method now returns a bytes object"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:190
msgid ""
"``.item`` now returns a ``bytes`` object instead of a buffer or byte array. "
"This may affect code which assumed the return value was mutable, which is no "
"longer the case."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:195
msgid ""
"``copy.copy`` and ``copy.deepcopy`` no longer turn ``masked`` into an array"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:196
msgid ""
"Since ``np.ma.masked`` is a readonly scalar, copying should be a no-op. "
"These functions now behave consistently with ``np.copy()``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:200
msgid "Multifield Indexing of Structured Arrays will still return a copy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:201
msgid ""
"The change that multi-field indexing of structured arrays returns a view "
"instead of a copy is pushed back to 1.16. A new method ``numpy.lib."
"recfunctions.repack_fields`` has been introduced to help mitigate the "
"effects of this change, which can be used to write code compatible with both "
"numpy 1.15 and 1.16. For more information on how to update code to account "
"for this future change see the \"accessing multiple fields\" section of the "
"`user guide <https://docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy/user/basics.rec.html>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:211
msgid "C API changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:214
msgid ""
"New functions ``npy_get_floatstatus_barrier`` and "
"``npy_clear_floatstatus_barrier``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:215
msgid ""
"Functions ``npy_get_floatstatus_barrier`` and "
"``npy_clear_floatstatus_barrier`` have been added and should be used in "
"place of the ``npy_get_floatstatus`` and ``npy_clear_status`` functions. "
"Optimizing compilers like GCC 8.1 and Clang were rearranging the order of "
"operations when the previous functions were used in the ufunc SIMD "
"functions, resulting in the floatstatus flags being checked before the "
"operation whose status we wanted to check was run.  See `#10339 <https://"
"github.com/numpy/numpy/issues/10370>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:224
msgid "Changes to ``PyArray_GetDTypeTransferFunction``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:225
msgid ""
"``PyArray_GetDTypeTransferFunction`` now defaults to using user-defined "
"``copyswapn`` / ``copyswap`` for user-defined dtypes. If this causes a "
"significant performance hit, consider implementing ``copyswapn`` to reflect "
"the implementation of ``PyArray_GetStridedCopyFn``.  See `#10898 <https://"
"github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/10898>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:233
msgid "New Features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:236
msgid "``np.gcd`` and ``np.lcm`` ufuncs added for integer and objects types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:237
msgid ""
"These compute the greatest common divisor, and lowest common multiple, "
"respectively. These work on all the numpy integer types, as well as the "
"builtin arbitrary-precision ``Decimal`` and ``long`` types."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:242
msgid "Support for cross-platform builds for iOS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:243
msgid ""
"The build system has been modified to add support for the "
"``_PYTHON_HOST_PLATFORM`` environment variable, used by ``distutils`` when "
"compiling on one platform for another platform. This makes it possible to "
"compile NumPy for iOS targets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:248
msgid ""
"This only enables you to compile NumPy for one specific platform at a time. "
"Creating a full iOS-compatible NumPy package requires building for the 5 "
"architectures supported by iOS (i386, x86_64, armv7, armv7s and arm64), and "
"combining these 5 compiled builds products into a single \"fat\" binary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:254
msgid "``return_indices`` keyword added for ``np.intersect1d``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:255
msgid ""
"New keyword ``return_indices`` returns the indices of the two input arrays "
"that correspond to the common elements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:259
msgid "``np.quantile`` and ``np.nanquantile``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:260
msgid ""
"Like ``np.percentile`` and ``np.nanpercentile``, but takes quantiles in [0, "
"1] rather than percentiles in [0, 100]. ``np.percentile`` is now a thin "
"wrapper around ``np.quantile`` with the extra step of dividing by 100."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:266
msgid "Build system"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:267
msgid "Added experimental support for the 64-bit RISC-V architecture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:271
msgid "Improvements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:274
msgid "``np.einsum`` updates"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:275
msgid ""
"Syncs einsum path optimization tech between `numpy` and `opt_einsum`. In "
"particular, the `greedy` path has received many enhancements by @jcmgray. A "
"full list of issues fixed are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:279
msgid "Arbitrary memory can be passed into the `greedy` path. Fixes gh-11210."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:280
msgid ""
"The greedy path has been updated to contain more dynamic programming ideas "
"preventing a large number of duplicate (and expensive) calls that figure out "
"the actual pair contraction that takes place. Now takes a few seconds on "
"several hundred input tensors. Useful for matrix product state theories."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:284
msgid ""
"Reworks the broadcasting dot error catching found in gh-11218 gh-10352 to be "
"a bit earlier in the process."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:286
msgid ""
"Enhances the `can_dot` functionality that previous missed an edge case (part "
"of gh-11308)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:290
msgid "``np.ufunc.reduce`` and related functions now accept an initial value"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:291
msgid ""
"``np.ufunc.reduce``, ``np.sum``, ``np.prod``, ``np.min`` and ``np.max`` all "
"now accept an ``initial`` keyword argument that specifies the value to start "
"the reduction with."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:296
msgid "``np.flip`` can operate over multiple axes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:297
msgid ""
"``np.flip`` now accepts None, or tuples of int, in its ``axis`` argument. If "
"axis is None, it will flip over all the axes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:301
msgid ""
"``histogram`` and ``histogramdd`` functions have moved to ``np.lib."
"histograms``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:302
msgid ""
"These were originally found in ``np.lib.function_base``. They are still "
"available under their un-scoped ``np.histogram(dd)`` names, and to maintain "
"compatibility, aliased at ``np.lib.function_base.histogram(dd)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:306
msgid ""
"Code that does ``from np.lib.function_base import *`` will need to be "
"updated with the new location, and should consider not using ``import *`` in "
"future."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:310
msgid "``histogram`` will accept NaN values when explicit bins are given"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:311
msgid ""
"Previously it would fail when trying to compute a finite range for the data. "
"Since the range is ignored anyway when the bins are given explicitly, this "
"error was needless."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:315
msgid ""
"Note that calling ``histogram`` on NaN values continues to raise the "
"``RuntimeWarning`` s typical of working with nan values, which can be "
"silenced as usual with ``errstate``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:320
msgid ""
"``histogram`` works on datetime types, when explicit bin edges are given"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:321
msgid ""
"Dates, times, and timedeltas can now be histogrammed. The bin edges must be "
"passed explicitly, and are not yet computed automatically."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:325
msgid "``histogram`` \"auto\" estimator handles limited variance better"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:326
msgid ""
"No longer does an IQR of 0 result in ``n_bins=1``, rather the number of bins "
"chosen is related to the data size in this situation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:330
msgid ""
"The edges returned by ``histogram`` and ``histogramdd`` now match the data "
"float type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:331
msgid ""
"When passed ``np.float16``, ``np.float32``, or ``np.longdouble`` data, the "
"returned edges are now of the same dtype. Previously, ``histogram`` would "
"only return the same type if explicit bins were given, and ``histogram`` "
"would produce ``float64`` bins no matter what the inputs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:337
msgid "``histogramdd`` allows explicit ranges to be given in a subset of axes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:338
msgid ""
"The ``range`` argument of `numpy.histogramdd` can now contain ``None`` "
"values to indicate that the range for the corresponding axis should be "
"computed from the data. Previously, this could not be specified on a per-"
"axis basis."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:343
msgid ""
"The normed arguments of ``histogramdd`` and ``histogram2d`` have been renamed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:344
msgid ""
"These arguments are now called ``density``, which is consistent with "
"``histogram``. The old argument continues to work, but the new name should "
"be preferred."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:349
msgid ""
"``np.r_`` works with 0d arrays, and ``np.ma.mr_`` works with ``np.ma.masked``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:350
msgid ""
"0d arrays passed to the `r_` and `mr_` concatenation helpers are now treated "
"as though they are arrays of length 1. Previously, passing these was an "
"error. As a result, `numpy.ma.mr_` now works correctly on the ``masked`` "
"constant."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:355
msgid "``np.ptp`` accepts a ``keepdims`` argument, and extended axis tuples"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:356
msgid ""
"``np.ptp`` (peak-to-peak) can now work over multiple axes, just like ``np."
"max`` and ``np.min``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:360
msgid "``MaskedArray.astype`` now is identical to ``ndarray.astype``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:361
msgid ""
"This means it takes all the same arguments, making more code written for "
"ndarray work for masked array too."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:365
msgid "Enable AVX2/AVX512 at compile time"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:366
msgid ""
"Change to simd.inc.src to allow use of AVX2 or AVX512 at compile time. "
"Previously compilation for avx2 (or 512) with -march=native would still use "
"the SSE code for the simd functions even when the rest of the code got AVX2."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:371
msgid ""
"``nan_to_num`` always returns scalars when receiving scalar or 0d inputs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:372
msgid ""
"Previously an array was returned for integer scalar inputs, which is "
"inconsistent with the behavior for float inputs, and that of ufuncs in "
"general. For all types of scalar or 0d input, the result is now a scalar."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:377
msgid "``np.flatnonzero`` works on numpy-convertible types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:378
msgid ""
"``np.flatnonzero`` now uses ``np.ravel(a)`` instead of ``a.ravel()``, so it "
"works for lists, tuples, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:382
msgid "``np.interp`` returns numpy scalars rather than builtin scalars"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:383
msgid ""
"Previously ``np.interp(0.5, [0, 1], [10, 20])`` would return a ``float``, "
"but now it returns a ``np.float64`` object, which more closely matches the "
"behavior of other functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:387
msgid ""
"Additionally, the special case of ``np.interp(object_array_0d, ...)`` is no "
"longer supported, as ``np.interp(object_array_nd)`` was never supported "
"anyway."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:390
msgid ""
"As a result of this change, the ``period`` argument can now be used on 0d "
"arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:394
msgid "Allow dtype field names to be unicode in Python 2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:395
msgid ""
"Previously ``np.dtype([(u'name', float)])`` would raise a ``TypeError`` in "
"Python 2, as only bytestrings were allowed in field names. Now any unicode "
"string field names will be encoded with the ``ascii`` codec, raising a "
"``UnicodeEncodeError`` upon failure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:400
msgid ""
"This change makes it easier to write Python 2/3 compatible code using ``from "
"__future__ import unicode_literals``, which previously would cause string "
"literal field names to raise a TypeError in Python 2."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:405
msgid ""
"Comparison ufuncs accept ``dtype=object``, overriding the default ``bool``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:406
msgid ""
"This allows object arrays of symbolic types, which override ``==`` and other "
"operators to return expressions, to be compared elementwise with ``np."
"equal(a, b, dtype=object)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:411
msgid "``sort`` functions accept ``kind='stable'``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:412
msgid "Up until now, to perform a stable sort on the data, the user must do:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:417
msgid ""
"because merge sort is the only stable sorting algorithm available in NumPy. "
"However, having kind='mergesort' does not make it explicit that the user "
"wants to perform a stable sort thus harming the readability."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:421
msgid ""
"This change allows the user to specify kind='stable' thus clarifying the "
"intent."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:425
msgid "Do not make temporary copies for in-place accumulation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:426
msgid ""
"When ufuncs perform accumulation they no longer make temporary copies "
"because of the overlap between input an output, that is, the next element "
"accumulated is added before the accumulated result is stored in its place, "
"hence the overlap is safe. Avoiding the copy results in faster execution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:432
msgid "``linalg.matrix_power`` can now handle stacks of matrices"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:433
msgid ""
"Like other functions in ``linalg``, ``matrix_power`` can now deal with "
"arrays of dimension larger than 2, which are treated as stacks of matrices. "
"As part of the change, to further improve consistency, the name of the first "
"argument has been changed to ``a`` (from ``M``), and the exceptions for non-"
"square matrices have been changed to ``LinAlgError`` (from ``ValueError``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:440
msgid ""
"Increased performance in ``random.permutation`` for multidimensional arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:441
msgid ""
"``permutation`` uses the fast path in ``random.shuffle`` for all input array "
"dimensions.  Previously the fast path was only used for 1-d arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:445
msgid ""
"Generalized ufuncs now accept ``axes``, ``axis`` and ``keepdims`` arguments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:446
msgid ""
"One can control over which axes a generalized ufunc operates by passing in "
"an ``axes`` argument, a list of tuples with indices of particular axes.  For "
"instance, for a signature of ``(i,j),(j,k)->(i,k)`` appropriate for matrix "
"multiplication, the base elements are two-dimensional matrices and these are "
"taken to be stored in the two last axes of each argument.  The corresponding "
"axes keyword would be ``[(-2, -1), (-2, -1), (-2, -1)]``. If one wanted to "
"use leading dimensions instead, one would pass in ``[(0, 1), (0, 1), (0, "
"1)]``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:454
msgid ""
"For simplicity, for generalized ufuncs that operate on 1-dimensional arrays "
"(vectors), a single integer is accepted instead of a single-element tuple, "
"and for generalized ufuncs for which all outputs are scalars, the (empty) "
"output tuples can be omitted.  Hence, for a signature of ``(i),(i)->()`` "
"appropriate for an inner product, one could pass in ``axes=[0, 0]`` to "
"indicate that the vectors are stored in the first dimensions of the two "
"inputs arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:461
msgid ""
"As a short-cut for generalized ufuncs that are similar to reductions, i.e., "
"that act on a single, shared core dimension such as the inner product "
"example above, one can pass an ``axis`` argument. This is equivalent to "
"passing in ``axes`` with identical entries for all arguments with that core "
"dimension (e.g., for the example above, ``axes=[(axis,), (axis,)]``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:467
msgid ""
"Furthermore, like for reductions, for generalized ufuncs that have inputs "
"that all have the same number of core dimensions and outputs with no core "
"dimension, one can pass in ``keepdims`` to leave a dimension with size 1 in "
"the outputs, thus allowing proper broadcasting against the original inputs. "
"The location of the extra dimension can be controlled with ``axes``. For "
"instance, for the inner-product example, ``keepdims=True, axes=[-2, -2, "
"-2]`` would act on the inner-product example, ``keepdims=True, axis=-2`` "
"would act on the one-but-last dimension of the input arguments, and leave a "
"size 1 dimension in that place in the output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:478
msgid "float128 values now print correctly on ppc systems"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:479
msgid ""
"Previously printing float128 values was buggy on ppc, since the special "
"double-double floating-point-format on these systems was not accounted for. "
"float128s now print with correct rounding and uniqueness."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:483
msgid ""
"Warning to ppc users: You should upgrade glibc if it is version <=2.23, "
"especially if using float128. On ppc, glibc's malloc in these version often "
"misaligns allocated memory which can crash numpy when using float128 values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:488
msgid "New ``np.take_along_axis`` and ``np.put_along_axis`` functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:489
msgid ""
"When used on multidimensional arrays, ``argsort``, ``argmin``, ``argmax``, "
"and ``argpartition`` return arrays that are difficult to use as indices. "
"``take_along_axis`` provides an easy way to use these indices to lookup "
"values within an array, so that::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:494
msgid "np.take_along_axis(a, np.argsort(a, axis=axis), axis=axis)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:496
msgid "is the same as::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:498
msgid "np.sort(a, axis=axis)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.15.0-notes.rst:500
msgid ""
"``np.put_along_axis`` acts as the dual operation for writing to these "
"indices within an array."
msgstr ""
